WEBVTT

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:30.000
COMPUTER:
 The directions for a human
 being are written in code

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
three billion letters long.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
These instructions tell
 our bodies how to live,

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.000
how to grow, how to die.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Researchers call this code
 "The Sequence."

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Captioning sponsored by THE
   U.S. DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:48.000
I'm Lucky Severson and this is
 Secrets of the Sequence.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
There was an obscure song
on the radio back in the '60s

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.000
that starts out, "Are you
a boy or are you a girl?

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
With your long, brown hair,
you look like a girl."

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
The singer is obviously confused
by outward appearances,

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
but to geneticists there
is almost no confusion.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
The genetics of sex are
virtually certain at conception,

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
though whether you're
a boy or a girl

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
seems to be
a toss of the genetic coin.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.000
COMPUTER:
On Sexual Determination:

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.000
In the human genome, there
are 23 pairs of chromosomes.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
For 22 of those pairs,

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.000
a chromosome
from the father teams up

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:27.000
with the same chromosome
from the mother.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
The 23rd pair is different.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
It can come in an X version
and a Y version.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
The egg always has
a single X chromosome.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Sperm can carry
either an X or a Y.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
If it's an X, the embryo
develops with an XX pair,

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
and it is female.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000
If the fertilizing sperm
carries a Y, it is a boy.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
Since you have to add something
to make a male,

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
clearly, the default human being
is female.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
Um, in any case, somewhere
there-- 83, 84, 85...

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
SEVERSON:
Dr. David Page
teaches and researches

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:04.000
the subject of sex chromosomes,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.000
and the Y chromosome
in particular.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Once it was established that
you were healthy enough to cry,

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
what was the next question
on your parents' mind,

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.000
on everybody else's mind?

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.000
AUDIENCE MEMBERS:
"Boy or a girl?"

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:20.000
"Boy or a girl,"
you got it.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
So how did your parents
or doctors

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
or whoever else
was in the delivery room,

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:27.000
how did they figure out whether
you were a boy or a girl?

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
( laughter )

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Well, there's a lot
of laughing here, uh...

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.000
So they took a look

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.000
and they saw whether
your external genitalia

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:40.000
were those of a male
or a female.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And so having determined

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
that you were a girl or a boy,
on this basis,

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
your parents could finally
decide what name to give you,

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
and they could announce
your existence to the world.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
SEVERSON:
David Page wears several hats
in the research community.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
He teaches biology
and genetics at MIT,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:02.000
conducts research
on the sex chromosomes

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.000
at the Whitehead Institute,
and gives public lectures.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
His current focus is to find out
why the Y, or male chromosome,

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
is unlike all the others
in the genome.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.000
PAGE:
A typical chromosome
has a few thousand genes.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
The Y chromosome has only about
40 or 50 different genes on it.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
So it's a relatively sparsely
populated, rural chromosome.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.000
But what are those genes?

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
There's a gene on the Y
chromosome called SRY--

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
that stands for sex-determining
region of the Y chromosome.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
The SRY gene on the Y chromosome
has a very important role

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
in all of our lives.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
SEVERSON:
Before fertilization,
the egg has the potential

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
to become either
a male or female embryo.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
The decision to develop ovaries
and be female

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
or develop testes and be male,

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
is made by a single gene
on the Y chromosome

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.000
called the SRY gene.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:03.000
PAGE:
So seven weeks after the egg
that gave rise to us

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.000
was fertilized by the sperm
that gave rise to us,

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.000
seven weeks after that happened,
the SRY gene, if it's present,

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
raises its hand
and says "I'm here"--

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
instructs a number
of other genes

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
to start the process
of making a testis.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:22.000
But then it disappears
and is never heard from again.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.000
SEVERSON:
That makes SRY a pretty
important male gene

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
and the Y chromosome
emphatically the male
chromosome.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.000
But what about
the other 50 genes on the Y?

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:36.000
PAGE:
Then there is the BLZ-2 locus,

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
which is self-confidence
unlinked to ability, um.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Then, identifying aircraft,
MOM-4-U,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.000
which is a fascination with
spiders and reptiles and such.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:51.000
No other chromosome

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
gets cartoons like this
made about it.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:56.000
The Y has suffered through years
and years of misunderstanding.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:00.000
SEVERSON:
So there are three types
of genes on the Y chromosome.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
SRY triggers the formation
of the testes.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
There's a type
of housekeeping genes

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
that regulate
basic cell functioning,

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
and another type,
like the DAZ gene,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
is responsible
for sperm production.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
PAGE:
So you have to keep them...

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:15.000
So, what's the story?

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
You have to keep them
pretty dense

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:18.000
to keep them from...

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Um, you have to keep them
at intermediate density.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
Yeah, they look pretty juicy
to me, pretty good.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
SEVERSON:
About one in every 4,000 boys

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
is born with a hole
in his Y chromosome

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
that causes male infertility.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:38.000
Page's lab is putting
human sperm-making genes

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:39.000
into infertile mice

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
to see which ones are the most
important to male fertility.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
PAGE:
In this case,
a defect has been produced

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
in a mouse spermatogenesis gene.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
We're going to see if we can do

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
a little gene therapy
on this mouse

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
and rescue that defect,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
using the human Y
spermatogenesis gene,

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
and that will, in turn, tell us

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
a lot about how the human
Y spermatogenesis gene works.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:06.000
SEVERSON:
Figure that out, and it could
lead to a fertility therapy.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
One in six American couples
is infertile,

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:12.000
and about one-third of the time
it's caused by the male.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
It's just one
of the genetic puzzles

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
that makes the Y chromosome
so important

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
to both males and females.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
The one question
that I'm asked most frequently

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
is what do these X and Y
chromosomes have to do

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:25.000
with... with sexual orientation?

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:27.000
Do these,
do the X and the Y chromosomes

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:30.000
make you straight or gay?

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
We don't yet understand much,
if anything,

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.000
about the connection
between the sex chromosomes

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
and how sexual identity, uh,
and sexual preference

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
is actually established
in the mind.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.000
Once the embryo decides
to make testes or ovaries

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
under the influence
or absence of SRY,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
then those-- the testis
or the ovary--

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:59.000
then produces sex hormones,
the famous things

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:02.000
like testosterone and estrogen
and so on.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
And these sex hormones
are actually responsible

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
for masculinizing or feminizing

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:09.000
many of the other
parts of the body,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
including,
it's thought, the brain.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
SEVERSON:
So now we know

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.000
what the difference
between girls and boys is--

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
a gene called SRY.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
The U.S. Senate
recently failed to act

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
on anti-cloning
legislation,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.000
which means there probably
won't be any this year,

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.000
but the issue is not going away.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.000
As one newspaper
headline put it,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
"Cloning has put the 'political'
back in 'science'."

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.000
That's literally true
in the case of Francis Fukuyama,

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
one of America's foremost
political scientists,

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:45.000
who also sits on the president's
Bioethics Council.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.000
In a new book, Our Posthuman
 Future, Fukuyama argues

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
that some of the most profound
and unprecedented changes

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:58.000
in history may be on the way.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
Of course, we've been changing
things about ourselves

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.000
since the beginning
of the species--

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
knowledge and abilities,
habits, appearance.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:09.000
FUKUYAMA:
The one thing

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
that they have not been able
to alter thus far is

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
the basic genetic makeup
of the human species,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:15.000
which is something

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:18.000
that was basically given to us
by evolution.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
And the "posthuman future"

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
refers to the prospect
down the road

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.000
that we will at some point

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
be able to consciously
take control of that process

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
of genetic design
and essentially reshape,

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
you know, what human beings
are by nature.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:42.000
SEVERSON:
Fukuyama warns of the social
and political consequences

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
of even
the most benign changes

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
like the fact
that we live longer.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.000
FUKUYAMA:
Europe in 50 years is going to
have a median age of about 60--

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
50% of the population
will be 60 years or older--

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
and that part of the world
will be surrounded

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
by a Third World, where the
median age is around 22 or 23.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
SEVERSON:
And issues with
even more profound implications

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
are on the horizon.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
FUKUYAMA:
Human germ-line engineering,
if it becomes possible,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
will be probably
the most consequential

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
simply because when you start
making these changes,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
they are irreversible--

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.000
they're handed down
to descendants.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
They really offer the chance

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
of changing
the fundamental structure

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.000
of what a human being is.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:28.000
SEVERSON:
Though the actual retooling
of the human genome

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
is a good ways off,
Fukuyama is convinced

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:33.000
that this science
is too important

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
to be left
entirely to the scientists.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:38.000
He wants a new regulatory agency

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.000
staffed both by scientists
and non-scientists.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
And it's not that scientists
have bad motives at all.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
I mean, they have
very good motives.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
But, you know, their interests
don't necessarily correspond

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:50.000
to the public interest,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
and so therefore,
I think there is a need

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
to somewhat democratize
that decision-making process.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
SEVERSON:
Can it be done--

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
fencing off areas prohibited
to scientific advance?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
Francis Fukuyama believes
it can, and he is not alone.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:05.000
MAN:
I think it would be

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.000
morally reprehensible
to despair at the possibility

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
of trying to exercise
some control

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
over where this engine is going.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
The atomic scientists
had a genie out of the bottle

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
at the end of World War II.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
The biologists
are in the same place.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
Dr. Leon Kass is also on
the president's bioethics panel.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
In fact, he chairs it.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
The group was set up last year

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
to advise the president
on the relevant issues.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
But the president didn't
even wait for its advice,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
instead immediately calling

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
for a total ban
on therapeutic cloning.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
For some background
on the issue,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
let's see what
our computer has on file.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
COMPUTER:
Therapeutic cloning--

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
or "somatic cell
nuclear transfer"--

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.000
involves removing the nucleus
from a human egg

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
and replacing it with the
nucleus of a cell from a donor.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
The nucleus contains the donor's
entire genetic code.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
As the egg divides,

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:07.000
it develops an inner core
of embryonic stem cells,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
which could be harvested
and returned to the donor

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
to replace
or repair damaged tissue

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
without the problem
of tissue rejection.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Some fear that permitting
therapeutic cloning

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
could lead
to reproductive cloning--

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
the cloning of human beings--
or even to manufacturing embryos

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:28.000
to harvest their healthy organs
for the sick and disabled.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:35.000
Our children... are gifts
to be loved and protected,

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
not products to be designed
and manufactured.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Allowing cloning would be taking
a significant step

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
toward a society
in which human beings

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:50.000
are grown for spare body parts

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:55.000
and children are engineered
to custom specifications,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.000
and that's not acceptable.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
SEVERSON:
But those who believe in the
promise of therapeutic cloning

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
reject that argument.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
MAN:
This...

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:09.000
clump of cells that will never
leave the laboratory

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
is not the union
of male and female.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
It's an egg

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
that gets its DNA
and its nucleus taken out.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
SEVERSON:
Hollywood Superman
Christopher Reeve was paralyzed

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
in a riding accident in 1995.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
Since then, he's learned
about-- and campaigned for--

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
research on
spinal cord injuries.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
He's convinced that stem cells
cloned from his own DNA

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
might heal his injured
spinal cord,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
enabling him to walk again.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:42.000
REEVE:
You're not even working
with an embryo;

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
you're working with an egg
that has not been fertilized.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
You must see the distinction.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:52.000
There are 400,000 people
with spinal cord injuries,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:56.000
and there are many, many more
who have other disabilities

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
that could have been helped
by saved stem cells.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.000
SEVERSON:
Not surprisingly, the Religious
Right sees it differently.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
JERRY FALWELL:
If it's embryonic
stem cell research,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:10.000
it all involves
the destruction of an embryo,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.000
and so it begins
with an abortion.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:17.000
I would say it's never right
to do wrong to accomplish right.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
SEVERSON:
So is this one of those
black-and-white issues,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
or a more shaded,
nuanced dilemma?

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
KASS:
What we're dealing with here
is not simply

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
a case of good versus evil,
but a case of competing goods,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
or a case where the evils,
such as they are,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
are so closely embedded
in the goods

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
that you can't simply
tease them out

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
without forgoing the one
or embracing the other.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
As a biologist,
I've come to somehow regard

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:45.000
the earliest stages of human
life as not humanly nothing.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:50.000
SEVERSON:
To other bioethicists, that
position seems simply wrong.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
The notion that potential
ingredients of people

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
are the same as people is one
that doesn't seem to me

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
to be factually correct.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:03.000
My personal view is that there
is a kind of rising moral status

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
that begins at conception

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
and continues, in fact,
until you become an adult.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
And so it would be permissible
to do certain things

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
with embryos that it would not
be permissible to do

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:17.000
with a later-stage fetus or
certainly with an actual infant.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.000
SEVERSON:
Both Fukuyama and Kass
would draw a red line

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.000
between repairing and
enhancement, or modification.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:28.000
Are these questions
that may affect the future

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:29.000
of the human species?

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And who should decide--

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
the scientists themselves
or government?

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
CAPLAN:
If you believe in choice,
and you don't want to wind up

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
with a government-imposed vision

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
of genetic normalcy
or genetic desirability,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.000
you've got to let people
make their choices,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
and I would allow some limits

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
if it turned out
that the choices

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:52.000
that individuals were making
about genetics

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
were skewing the safety
or stability of a society.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Science is, by its
own self-definition,

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
morally neutral,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:05.000
whereas if you've got moral
dimensions to a question,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:10.000
those are really for the
community as a whole to decide.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:14.000
The debate will go on, whatever
congress and the president do

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.000
because of the profound
importance of these issues

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
to the human--
or posthuman-- future.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
There are two kinds of
cloning:

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
reproductive and therapeutic.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
Reproductive cloning seeks
to reproduce

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
entire living organisms,
and we've done this

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.000
with goats, cats, sheep,
cows, mice and pigs.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
Therapeutic cloning,
on the other hand, seeks

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
to create not a whole organism,
but just a few special cells

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
that might be used
to grow new tissue

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
or reverse genetic diseases.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
COMPUTER:
Lucky, there's a problem
with the term "therapeutic"

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
in connection with cloning.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:51.000
Many scientists insist

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
that creating duplicate cells
for medical experimentation

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
be called
"nuclear transplantation"

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
or "stem cell research."

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
They think
that calling it "cloning"

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
raises too many red flags.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:05.000
To a layman I'm not sure

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.000
"nuclear transplantation" sounds
that much more benign,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:11.000
but let's begin
at the beginning.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:14.000
COMPUTER:
About cloning:

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:17.000
The word "clone" comes
from the Greek word klon,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
which means "twig"
or "offshoot."

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
A clone is an identical copy
of something.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
In genetics
it means genetically identical.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
Cloning is
nonsexual reproduction.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
It does not require the union

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
of male and female gametes,
or sex cells.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:36.000
Genetic material from a donor
is inserted in an egg,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
which has had
its own nucleus removed.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:39.000
When the egg divides,

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.000
it will reproduce
the inserted genetic material.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
SEVERSON:
There is widespread agreement

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
that the reproductive cloning
of human beings

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
is and should remain taboo.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.000
We just don't know enough

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
to guarantee that a cloned baby
would be born healthy,

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
but many favor
therapeutic cloning,

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:03.000
and that research is under way
in a number of laboratories.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
This is how it works.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
First the cloners need eggs.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.000
They remove the genetic material
from the egg and discard it.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:12.000
These are skin cells

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
from a mammal
that's going to be cloned.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
Each dark spot

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
is a nucleus containing the
genetic material of the cell.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:23.000
The nucleus is extracted
from the rest of the cell

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
for use in the empty egg.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:29.000
One skin cell nucleus
is injected into each empty egg

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:31.000
so the genetic instructions
that came with the egg

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
have been replaced

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
with the genetic instructions
from the skin cell.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:38.000
After electrical
and chemical manipulation,

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:41.000
a few of these cells may begin
to grow into embryos.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:45.000
Once scientists have mastered
the creation and nurturing

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
of these embryos long enough
for stem cells to develop,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
they can explore
the possibilities

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
for organ and tissue repair.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:56.000
MAN:
With therapeutic cloning, you're
starting out with one cell,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
and that one cell becomes two,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.000
then those two become four,
the four become eight,

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
and then you're
actually watching this

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:04.000
under the microscope,
and you can see

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:07.000
once you get to a certain level
and a certain volume of cells,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.000
there's an approximate volume
of cells

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
where you can actually take
the cells and start using them

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
for different purposes.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:18.000
You can convert these cells
into different tissue structures

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:22.000
whether it be heart muscle,
skeletal muscle,

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:23.000
cartilage, bone, et cetera,

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:27.000
and you can then expand these
cells into large quantities

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:30.000
and have them available
for the patient.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:34.000
SEVERSON:
Dr. Atala is talking
about human embryonic stem cells

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:37.000
from which he hopes
to grow completely new organs.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.000
It's called tissue engineering.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
He could use the stem cells
already approved

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:43.000
by the U.S. government

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
but they don't solve
one important basic problem:

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
They don't come
from the patient who needs them.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:52.000
ATALA:
The fact is that
even if you are able

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.000
to obtain stem cells
from embryonic sources

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.000
and even if you are able
to differentiate those cells

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
and even if you are able
to take those cells

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
and create tissue for therapy,

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
once you go through
that whole process,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:11.000
there is no guarantee
that once it gets to the patient

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:14.000
that patient is not going
to reject it,

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:18.000
because it's not recognizing
that tissue as their own.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And that is where therapeutic
cloning can provide an answer,

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
because you're not using
somebody else's cells.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.000
You're using
the patient's own cells,

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
and that makes a big difference.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
SEVERSON:
Dr. Atala collaborates

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.000
with Robert Lanza
of Advanced Cell Technology,

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:39.000
a biotech company
in Worcester, Massachusetts.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:43.000
Despite all the controversy,
ACT has staked its future

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
on therapeutic
cloning technology

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:49.000
for both organ replacement
and cell therapy.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.000
LANZA:
Our objective is actually
to not to clone a whole copy

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
of a person or a whole animal

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:55.000
but to basically
just clone cells.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.000
We want to clone cells

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:59.000
that can be used
for replacement purposes.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
You know, there are literally
hundreds and hundreds

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:04.000
of diseases that this technology
could be used to treat--

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:05.000
for instance,
Parkinson's disease.

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:07.000
If you wanted
to put in new neurons

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
or if you had kidney failure
or heart failure,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:12.000
we could grow you up
either new heart cells

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:15.000
or even eventually
an entire heart.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:20.000
SEVERSON:
The controversy arises because
a potential life is destroyed

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.000
to obtain those stem cells.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.000
LANZA:
We're talking about
a microscopic ball of cells

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:27.000
that doesn't have
a single body cell yet.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:31.000
It hasn't even decided
what it wants to do.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
So the question here is
is whether or not you're going

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.000
to take this microscopic ball
of cells

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:38.000
and alleviate a lifetime
of suffering in a patient

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
or whether or not
you're just going to discard it.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:42.000
I think the whole question is

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:46.000
is whether or not a completely
undifferentiated ball of cells

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
that's microscopic--
smaller than the head of a pin--

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
warrants the same rights
and reverence

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
as an adult or a child
who may die

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
because we failed
to use this technology.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:59.000
If someone took that cloned ball
of undifferentiated cells

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
and implanted it
in a human uterus,

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:06.000
could it be used to reproduce
a living, breathing human being?

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
The troubling answer is "Yes."

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:11.000
Should we ban therapeutic
cloning of human beings

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
which might help millions

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.000
to prevent reproductive cloning
of humans?

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
That's a harder question
to answer.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
...substantially
to the placenta.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
SEVERSON:
Rudolf Jaenisch
of the Whitehead Institute

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:24.000
in Cambridge, Massachusetts,

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.000
thinks the scientific reasons

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:28.000
not to clone a living
human being are very strong.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
Based on studies
of cloned animals

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:33.000
and his own cloning research,
he believes that the process

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.000
of reproductive cloning
is too unpredictable

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:38.000
and imperfect to try
on a human being,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:42.000
and he is scornful of those
who are attempting to do it.

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:47.000
JAENISCH:
They need to be stopped,
because what will come out,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:49.000
and I think we are pretty...

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:52.000
I think it's with
quite some, um, confidence

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:54.000
we can predict this.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:58.000
What they will produce
are abnormal people,

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:01.000
and, um, you don't want
to use people as guinea pigs.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:05.000
SEVERSON:
But Jaenisch feels differently
about therapeutic cloning,

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:08.000
which he believes could
create embryonic stem cells

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
and lead to cures for diseases.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
JAENISCH:
Now, these embryonic stem cells

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
are really amazing cells.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:17.000
They have the potential
to... in culture

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:21.000
to develop into any tissue type
of your body.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.000
So they are shown that they...

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:27.000
We know they can develop
into neurons and nerve cells,

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:30.000
into, um, muscle cells,
into heart muscle cells,

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:33.000
into blood cells,
um, into cartilage,

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:34.000
into bone, into anything.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:37.000
They are now a source

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:41.000
of any tissue type
you might want to use

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:44.000
to transplant back
into the donor

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.000
and of course since genetically
they are identical,

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
the immune system
wouldn't mind that.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:53.000
It wouldn't reject those cells.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.000
There is the potential of what
we call regenerative medicine

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.000
or transplantation medicine,
and this is all

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:04.000
under the umbrella term
"therapeutic cloning."

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:07.000
You know, Great Britain
has banned reproductive cloning

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:12.000
but is allowing research
into human cloning for
therapeutic purposes to proceed.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:15.000
Meanwhile, a bill to ban
human cloning of any kind

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:18.000
for therapeutic
or reproductive purposes

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:21.000
is moving very slowly
through the U.S. Congress.

