00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.000
we'll explore the ethical
dimensions of the cloning debate

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.000
and hear from two men who have
very different perspectives:

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:32.000
the Reverend Jerry Falwell
and actor Christopher Reeve.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
When we think about patents

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:37.000
we usually think
about inventors:

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:40.000
Gutenberg
and the printing press,

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:41.000
Morse and the telegraph,

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:44.000
Marconi and the radio.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:47.000
We can understand patents
for inventions like these,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:48.000
but what about genes?

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:49.000
That's right, genes.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:51.000
There's a new
gold rush going on

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:53.000
with scientists staking claims
for treasure,

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:57.000
except this time,
the treasure is part of you.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:58.000
( computer beeps )

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
COMPUTER:
About patents.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:03.000
The word comes from the Latin
 litterae patentes,

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:05.000
meaning an open letter.

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:07.000
Such letters were used
by medieval monarchs

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:09.000
to confer rights and privileges.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:13.000
With a royal seal, the letters
served as proof of those rights

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:15.000
for all to see.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:18.000
The first recorded patent
of invention was granted

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:19.000
to John of Utynam.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:22.000
In 1449, he was awarded
a 20-year monopoly

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:27.000
for a glass-making process
previously unknown in England.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:30.000
The first patent this year
in the United States

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:34.000
was assigned number 6,334,220

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:37.000
for an adjustable disposable
garment protector--

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:40.000
a bib for motorists
eating fast foods.

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:44.000
Well, that's all
very interesting

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
but not really
to the point of our story.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:48.000
The question is,

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:51.000
do scientists have the right
to patent our genes,

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:53.000
to claim rights
to a piece of DNA

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:57.000
that is our shared inheritance,
and make money on it?

00:24:57.000 --> 00:24:58.000
Let's meet a family

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:02.000
who decided to take the matter
into their own hands.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:10.000
Living in a well-tended suburb
of Boston, Massachusetts

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.000
used to be everything
the Terry family wanted.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:17.000
Now their American dream is
pinned on something else:

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
a gene patent.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
Pat Terry used to be
a contractor

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:25.000
hired to solve the problems of
building biotech laboratories.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.000
Now he runs PXE International,

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:31.000
a nonprofit foundation that
may someday find a solution

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:34.000
to a very specific
genetic problem.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:37.000
MAN:
Five years ago I didn't know
a gene from a hubcap.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:40.000
I did not have any experience
whatsoever in this realm.

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.000
But after my children
were diagnosed,

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:46.000
I had to become an expert
and learn as much as I can.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:49.000
SEVERSON:
Pat's children,
Elizabeth and Ian,

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.000
were diagnosed with a disease

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:55.000
called pseudoxanthoma elasticum,
or PXE.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:58.000
PXE attacks the connective
tissues of the skin, eyes

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
and cardiovascular system,

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:04.000
causing problems like severe
skin lesions, vision loss

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:07.000
and even sudden cardiac arrest.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:09.000
And there is no known cure.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:13.000
In December 1994, the Terry
family got the diagnosis

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:15.000
that changed their lives.

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:16.000
WOMAN:
I was with the kids alone.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
I called Pat and told him
what the diagnosis was.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
I don't think
it really hit us completely.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
We tried to get
some information.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
The information was scattered.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:26.000
We got scared.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.000
We did things
like bought the kids

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:30.000
everything they wanted
for Christmas that year.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
And we booked
a trip to Europe,

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:35.000
thinking that they would die
by the time they were 13 or 14

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:37.000
was the news we got.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:40.000
SEVERSON:
Only one in 25,000 people
have PXE,

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:44.000
so profits from any drug therapy
would be small.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:47.000
Giving scientists motivation
to find a cure

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:50.000
for such a rare disorder
was a tall order,

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
but the Terrys were determined.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:55.000
Using the Internet--
and using up their savings--

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:58.000
they collected data
and tissue samples

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.000
from 1,500 PXE patients.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:03.000
They offered this unique
collection to researchers

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:06.000
and worked with scientists
to identify the gene.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
Two years ago,
PXE International,

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
along with the gene's
co-founder,

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
the University of Hawaii,

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:15.000
applied for a patent
on the PXE gene.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:16.000
SHARON TERRY:
I think the biggest difference

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:19.000
between corporate-structure
America patenting
and us patenting

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:20.000
is motivation.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And we have no problem

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.000
with corporate America
needing to make money,

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
because that's what
they need to do.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
In fact we want them
to do that,

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:29.000
because they will make
better drugs

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:31.000
and they will make
disease treatments.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:32.000
But for us it's
pure motivation

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:35.000
in terms of the patient
or the person affected.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.000
SEVERSON:
Since filing the patent,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:41.000
researchers found out that
the PXE gene is also involved

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:44.000
in cardiovascular disease
and macular degeneration--

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
diseases affecting millions.

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:49.000
That means their patent may have
wide application,

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.000
and that should entice
pharmaceutical companies

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
to research the gene
and what it does.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.000
For the Terrys
it's the means to the end--

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
finding a cure
for their children.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:03.000
Hi, Donna, is Nancy Taylor
available, please?

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:05.000
PAT TERRY:
It's a slightly different
business model

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
because we will be subsidizing
this patent

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:09.000
because it may not have
an economic engine

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:10.000
to survive on its own.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.000
So we might be
subsidizing access

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:14.000
or leveraging access

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:17.000
through the patent
and licensing system

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:19.000
that is a little
out of the ordinary.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:21.000
SEVERSON:
Many researchers believe

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:24.000
that what the Terrys are doing
is a model

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:27.000
for how gene patenting
should work for patients.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:30.000
But initially, gene patents
were filed for profits,

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.000
not for cures and therapies.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:37.000
MAN:
It's a very simple matter:
no patent, no drug.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:41.000
A drug company manufactures
a human component.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:44.000
All the research
that went into that

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.000
costs hundreds of millions
of dollars.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:51.000
If that research had not been
protected with patents,

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:53.000
nobody would do that research.

00:28:53.000 --> 00:28:56.000
Nobody owns a gene
in anybody's human body.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:59.000
But if we have taken that gene
from a body,

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:02.000
we've learned how to use it
to make a substance.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:07.000
That substance is useful
for medicine like insulin.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:11.000
Then it's deemed
the subject for patents,

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:14.000
and they're very important
for the future of medicine.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:18.000
SEVERSON:
But determining
legal ownership of a gene

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:21.000
that's held commonly by everyone
is pretty complicated.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Allowing the patenting
of human genes

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:27.000
would be like allowing Columbus
to patent America

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
or Newton to patent gravity

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:32.000
and make all of us pay for the
privilege of living in America

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.000
or being subject to gravity.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:35.000
That's what happens

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:37.000
when you allow the patenting
of a product of nature.

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.000
This should not be a part
of our patent law.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:41.000
And it takes something
that we all own

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:44.000
and should own as a community,
and lets a corporation own it

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:47.000
and make us pay for
the privilege of using it.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.000
SEVERSON:
The National Institutes
of Health

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:53.000
were among the first
institutions to patent genes.

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:56.000
Since the Human Genome Project
was paid for

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:57.000
by the American public,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.000
it seemed to follow that
the ownership of human genes

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:04.000
would be held in the public
domain, for everyone to use.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:05.000
It didn't happen
that way, though.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:09.000
MAN:
Whenever anybody says, "Well,
should that be patented?"

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:13.000
my rejoinder is, "Well, would it
help the public if it were?"

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:15.000
And if the answer is yes,
then let's look at that.

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:16.000
If the answer is no,
why are we doing that?

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
On the other hand,

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:21.000
if you're talking about snippets
of DNA of no known function

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:23.000
that somebody just wants to say,
"Now I own that piece.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
"There's a fence around it.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.000
Nobody can work on this
without asking my permission,"

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.000
that doesn't help
the public at all.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:30.000
That does just the reverse.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:32.000
It basically puts
a "No Fishing" sign

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:34.000
across a whole lot of the genome

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:36.000
and ends up slowing down
the progress of research.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.000
He was too young to say,
"Don't take my picture now."

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:48.000
SEVERSON:
The last thing
the Terrys want to do

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:50.000
is slow the progress of research
on the PXE gene,

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:55.000
and they plan to give wide
access to their discoveries.

00:30:55.000 --> 00:30:57.000
SHARON TERRY:
Our intention
in patenting the gene

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.000
was to have a place
at the table,

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:00.000
to be a part of the discussion,

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:03.000
to be a part of the plans
that would go forward from here,

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:06.000
and probably
most importantly,
to safeguard

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:07.000
what would happen
for patients

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.000
that, because we're
motivated first

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:11.000
by making sure
patients benefit,

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:13.000
we would be the voice
at the table

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:14.000
who would
constantly say,

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
"Is this the best path
for patients?"

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:20.000
PAT TERRY:
The reality for us to see
how rare-disease diagnostics

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
once the gene is found
or whatever,

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:24.000
the excitement is over,

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.000
the discovery process
is perceived to be over

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:31.000
by the scientific community and
they move on to another disease.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.000
And we felt
that we had

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:36.000
the long-term interests
close to our hearts.

00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:39.000
This is a nice
picture, too.

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:40.000
There are some doctors and
researchers

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:44.000
who want to replace the dog
as man's best friend

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:45.000
with the pig.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:48.000
Specifically, a variety
called "miniature swine,"

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:51.000
which top out
at a mere 300 pounds,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:54.000
well below the 1,000 or so
of adult swine.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:57.000
These smaller pigs
won't be pets though;

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.000
they'll be organ donors.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:00.000
After some
genetic modifications,

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:04.000
their organs may be used
to save human lives.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.000
It's called a "xenograft."

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:11.000
COMPUTER:
Xenograft comes from
the Greek word, "xenos,"

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:14.000
which means "stranger"
or "guest."

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:18.000
Xenophobia is fear and hatred
of anything foreign or strange.

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:20.000
Xenografts are
tissue transplants

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:22.000
from one species to another--

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.000
from a pig to a human,
for example.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.000
Normally the recipient's
immune system

00:32:27.000 --> 00:32:29.000
would reject
such a transplant.

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:32.000
Human-to-human transplants
are called "allografts."

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:35.000
In this case, the immune system
needs to be suppressed

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:36.000
to avoid rejection.

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:39.000
Autografts are transplants
from one place to another

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:41.000
on the same human.

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:45.000
The immune system has no problem
here; it likes its own kind.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:51.000
( heart rate machine bleeping )

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:52.000
SEVERSON:
For some 20 years now,

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:56.000
human-to-human transplants
seem to have worked pretty well.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:59.000
So why even bother
with xenografts from pigs,

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:02.000
with all the immune-response
problems?

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:05.000
MAN:
The reason why we are all so
interested in the xenotransplant

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:08.000
is because, paradoxically,

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:11.000
the success of ordinary,
allogenic transplants

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:14.000
has been so great that
we have run out of organs.

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:16.000
There just aren't
enough cadaver organs

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.000
to satisfy the need
for all the people

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:22.000
whose lives could be saved
by a transplant.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:24.000
That's why we're really working
so hard on this;

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:27.000
it's because people
are dying every day.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:30.000
SEVERSON:
Right now, there are
about 80,000 patients

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:33.000
on waiting lists
in the United States alone

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:35.000
for various donor organs.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.000
By all accounts,

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:41.000
16 people die each day
for want of a human donor organ.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:45.000
David Sachs believes that
pig organs can fill the gap.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:46.000
SACHS:
We would match

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
the donor to be the same size
as the recipient.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
So for an adult
who weighed 70 kilograms,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.000
we'd use a 70-kilogram pig.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:57.000
WOMAN:
It's incredibly surprising
how similar the pig is to man.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:01.000
It wouldn't be your choice
of your most-related relative.

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.000
But when you look at things
like heart rate, blood pressure,

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:08.000
serum chemistries,
the pig has...

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:12.000
shares an incredible amount, in
terms of physiology, with man.

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:20.000
SEVERSON:
So physically,
pigs are a lot like people.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:23.000
Genetically, there are some
significant differences

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.000
between pigs and humans.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:26.000
Powerful drugs are already used

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:30.000
to suppress the immune response
to a human organ transplant.

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.000
The amount of drugs needed

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:35.000
to suppress
the human immune response

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:38.000
to an unmodified pig organ
could be lethal.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:41.000
The major barrier
to xenotransplantation

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:42.000
is rejection--

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
the immune response
against that transplant--

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.000
and there are two ways we
are trying to overcome that:

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:53.000
One is by modifying the donor
through genetic engineering,

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.000
changing some
of the antigens on the pig--

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:58.000
the ones that are most difficult
to overcome--

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:00.000
and changing those
such that there will be

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:03.000
much less of an immune
response to them.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:07.000
And the other is by changing the
immune response of the recipient

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:11.000
in a specific way, which we call
"inducing tolerance."

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:14.000
SEVERSON:
Basically, it means making pigs
a little less piglike

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:17.000
and humans
a little more pig-tolerant.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:21.000
It's working toward
a genetic middle ground.

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:24.000
For example, pigs normally
carry a gene missing in humans,

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:28.000
one that generates a sugar
our bodies recognize as foreign.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.000
At the beginning of the year,

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
two biotechnology companies
announced

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:36.000
that they had cloned piglets
with that gene knocked out.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:38.000
SACHS:
It turns out

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:41.000
that on all species except
humans and old-world primates,

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:43.000
the terminal sugar--

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:46.000
the last sugar
on the surface of all cells,

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:49.000
on the sugars on all cells--
is alpha 1-3 gau.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.000
But sometime during evolution,

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:56.000
old-world primates and humans
lost the enzyme for that sugar.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.000
So we don't have alpha 1-3 gau,

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:01.000
and therefore we make
a lot of antibody against it.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:03.000
That antibody appears to be

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:07.000
one of the major barriers
to xenotransplantation.

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:11.000
SEVERSON:
Modifying pig organ donors
is half the equation.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:15.000
Making human recipients more
tolerant is coming along, too.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:18.000
The human thymus is where white
blood cells are programmed

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
to recognize invaders.

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:23.000
By injecting pig cells
in or near the thymus,

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:26.000
some white cells are trained
to accept pig tissues.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:28.000
This has worked in baboons,

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:31.000
which serve as
the humanlike animal model.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.000
But there is another concern:
pigs have something

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.000
called "porcine
endogenous retroviruses,"

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:40.000
retroviruses that are part
of the animal's own DNA.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:43.000
GREENSTEIN:
Every species
has endogenous retroviruses,

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:46.000
and so in human transplantation

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:49.000
by transplanting an organ
from one human to another,

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:53.000
you're not exposing the human
to a new endogenous retrovirus.

00:36:53.000 --> 00:36:59.000
We all have these pieces or
fragments of DNA in our genome.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.000
The issue in xenotransplantation

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:05.000
is that we
are potentially introducing

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:08.000
a new endogenous retrovirus
into the patient.

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:11.000
SEVERSON:
Viruses that jump
from one species to another

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
can behave badly.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:16.000
A virus, jumping from
monkey to human, for instance,

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:20.000
may have led to the disease
known to us as AIDS.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.000
Tackling the virus problem
has taken time.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:26.000
So has everything else
about xenograft research.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.000
This project at Massachusetts
General Hospital

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:30.000
is now in its 12th year.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:32.000
But now the pace
of tissue engineering research

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.000
is picking up.

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:39.000
So the question is,
will these pigs ever fly?

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:43.000
GREENSTEIN:
We've moved the survival of pig
organs in preclinical models

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:45.000
from minutes to hours to 30 days

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:49.000
to, in the extreme, almost
100 days of survival time.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:53.000
Now, we think we'll be able
to put together our protocols

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:55.000
in the next year and a half
to two,

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:58.000
and once we have survival times

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
on the order of six months
to a year,

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
we'll be able to start

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:06.000
very small, carefully controlled
clinical trials.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.000
The idea of knowing our roots,

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:12.000
where we came from is
almost irresistible.

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:16.000
And nowhere is it practiced
more faithfully and expertly

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:19.000
than within the Mormon Church,
headquartered in Salt Lake City.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:21.000
Mormons trace their lineage

00:38:21.000 --> 00:38:23.000
in order to collect names
of dead ancestors

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:27.000
so members can perform what are
called "baptisms for the dead."

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:31.000
But genealogy has long been
overlooked by technology.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:34.000
The advent of the Internet
sped up the process enormously,

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:37.000
but it's genetics
that has revolutionized

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:39.000
the study of the family tree.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:44.000
( camera shutter clicking )

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:47.000
SEVERSON:
People have been tracing
their family trees

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:48.000
since biblical times.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.000
And after the Second World War,

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
genealogy--
the study of human ancestry--

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.000
became an even
more popular hobby.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:58.000
I don't think that
I've ever met a person

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
who isn't interested
in who they are

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:03.000
and how they're connected
to other people

00:39:03.000 --> 00:39:05.000
and essentially
everybody else in the world.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.000
With this ring,
I thee wed.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
SEVERSON:
Tracing your heritage
isn't easy.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
Family trees never
stop branching out,

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:16.000
which means they create

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:20.000
increasingly complex
relationships between relatives.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:22.000
Grandparents die,
children move away,

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:25.000
there's divorce and remarriage.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:28.000
So genealogies can
often hit a dead end.

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:31.000
Family secrets slowly
become hidden in history.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
But DNA--
our definitive family record--

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:39.000
has the capacity to expose
genealogical connections

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
like never before.

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:45.000
Diahan Southard
of Relative Genetics in Utah

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:49.000
is helping to amass
a DNA database.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:52.000
There's tons of things you
can learn about your ancestry

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:53.000
on paper.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
But there's even more, I think,

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:57.000
you can learn about
your ancestry through DNA,

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:00.000
as paper only goes so far and
it can only tell you so much.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.000
But your DNA
really does reveal...

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:05.000
It carries everything
there is to know about you.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:08.000
SEVERSON:
So mysteries that have
long stumped archivists--

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
tracking where families
have moved,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:12.000
finding long-lost relatives--

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:15.000
these and other mysteries
now might be solved

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.000
through DNA analysis.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:19.000
Relative Genetics
is just one

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:21.000
of several companies
in the United States

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:25.000
offering DNA analysis to amateur
and professional genealogists.

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:27.000
DNA samples are
typically collected

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.000
by scraping cells
from inside the mouth.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:33.000
Technicians and
million-dollar gene machines

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:36.000
then extract strands
of the subject's DNA

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:37.000
and replicate or amplify it

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:41.000
using a technique called
polymerase chain reaction.

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:48.000
COMPUTER: 
About PCR:
polymerase chain reaction.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
PCR has transformed
molecular biology

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:53.000
through vastly extending
the capacity

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:56.000
to identify, manipulate
and reproduce DNA,

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:59.000
allowing scientists
to analyze genetic samples

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:01.000
that previously
could not be tested

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:05.000
because of poor quality
or small amounts.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:10.000
The starting material for PCR
is the "target sequence,"

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:12.000
a gene or segment of DNA.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.000
The complementary strands

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:18.000
of a double-stranded molecule
of DNA are separated by heating.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
Within a short time,

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:23.000
millions of exact replicas
of the target sequence

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:24.000
will have been produced

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.000
through repeated heating
and cooling cycles.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:30.000
This process is known
as PCR amplification

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:35.000
and creates enough DNA
for identification and research.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:42.000
SEVERSON:
Old techniques allowed
genealogists to track

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
maternal and paternal lines
separately,

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.000
but couldn't cross-reference
the data.

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:49.000
DNA analysis
will be able to do both.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:51.000
SOUTHARD:
It's easy for genealogists

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:53.000
because genealogy
is based on surnames

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:55.000
and it's based on tracking
the name of someone

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:57.000
to the name of someone else.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:41:59.000
And so when you're tracking
the name of someone,

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:03.000
you're also tracking their DNA,
and that's what we're using.

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:07.000
SEVERSON:
Still, family tree research
using mitochondrial DNA

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:10.000
and y chromosome analysis
has some flaws.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:13.000
If a mother bore only sons
for one generation,

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:15.000
her link to the future
was broken.

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:18.000
The same can be said for a
father who sired only daughters.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.000
Southard, along with researchers

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:25.000
at Brigham Young University
in Utah, are collecting

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:28.000
genealogical
and genetic information

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:30.000
from 100,000 individuals
around the globe,

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:33.000
representing the world's
different populations.

00:42:33.000 --> 00:42:34.000
They are conducting DNA analysis

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:38.000
on samples from every individual
in a massive database,

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.000
testing for patterns

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:44.000
not just in the y chromosome
and mitochondrial DNA,

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:48.000
but 250 varied points
on the complete human genome.

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:51.000
SOUTHARD:
Then you see what's common
about their genealogy

00:42:51.000 --> 00:42:53.000
and what's common
about their genetics,

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:56.000
and when those two things
overlap, then we've found

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:59.000
a genetic marker
that identifies that population.

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:02.000
You compare them one person
to another, and you can see

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:05.000
how each individual
is unique on their own,

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.000
and yet how they share

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:11.000
with different people who
descend from the same area.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:16.000
SEVERSON:
The scientist responsible
for this ambitious project

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:17.000
is Scott Woodward.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:21.000
WOODWARD:
We can reconstruct
gene pools in the past.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.000
We can now type an individual
who doesn't know anything

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
about their genealogy
or who they are

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:29.000
and tell them, with a high
degree of probability,

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:31.000
where their genes were

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:35.000
a generation ago, two, three,
four, five generations ago.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:37.000
It's useful mostly
because it doesn't lie.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:40.000
While your paper trail
could lead you

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.000
in completely
the wrong direction,

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:44.000
while you will run into two men

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.000
who have the same name--
John Wilson--

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:50.000
you will never run into two men
who have the same DNA.

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:57.000
SEVERSON:
But DNA reveals the truth:
we are all related,

00:43:57.000 --> 00:43:59.000
and more closely
than we might think.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:02.000
WOODWARD:
Everyone has two parents.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:06.000
They have four grandparents
and eight great-grandparents,

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:09.000
and if you keep going back
for 30 generations,

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:13.000
there are one billion potential
ancestors for each one of us.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:15.000
We share ancestors.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:18.000
There weren't enough people
living on the earth

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:20.000
to take care
of each one of us to have

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:25.000
one billion unique ancestors,
unique ancestors 750 years ago.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:28.000
So that means we all essentially
have married our cousins.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:32.000
And genealogy is a way
of discovering that.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.000
Evolution has been at work

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:40.000
since the first single-cell
organism appeared

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.000
some three and a half billion
years ago.

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.000
It has taken that long
for natural selection

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:47.000
to produce an animal
that could study evolution.

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:49.000
As we study our own development,

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:52.000
we have made some
interesting discoveries.

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.000
By analyzing our
mitochondrial DNA,

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:59.000
we can trace our lineage back
some 150,000 years

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:01.000
to the ancestral
mother of all humans,

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:04.000
the so-called African,
or mitochondrial, "Eve"

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:08.000
that all humans seem to share
as their original mother.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:10.000
A British researcher,
Bryan Sykes,

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:13.000
thinks that most who claim
European ancestry

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:17.000
are descended from seven
so-called "Daughters of Eve"

00:45:17.000 --> 00:45:20.000
who existed from 10,000
to 45,000 years ago.

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:23.000
He's got a company now,
Oxford Ancestors it's called--

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:25.000
Sykes is a professor at Oxford--

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.000
and they recently mailed me
this DNA kit

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:30.000
to see which of the
seven Daughters of Eve

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:32.000
I might have descended from.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.000
You've probably
seen this before--

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:37.000
a swab to scrape cells
from inside a cheek,

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:38.000
the sort of thing you do

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:41.000
to prove that you really are
heir to all those millions

00:45:41.000 --> 00:45:43.000
and that you're not
a monkey's uncle.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.000
Let me read the directions.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:47.000
It says, "Rinse your mouth
with water

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:52.000
"to remove food
and other debris.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:53.000
"Remove the brush
from its pocket,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:58.000
"taking care not to touch
the bristles with you fingers.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:05.000
"Rub the bristles on your inner
cheek five times on each side.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:07.000
"Try to avoid touching
your teeth,

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:10.000
"as bacteria collect there.

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:13.000
Replace the brush
inside the pocket."

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:17.000
Seal it, and send it off,
back to England,

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:19.000
and in a few weeks
they promise to let me know

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:22.000
who my greatest of
all grandmothers was--

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:25.000
perhaps Ursula or Helena
or Xenia.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.000
Wasn't she a warrior princess?

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:29.000
Tara?

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:31.000
Who picked these names,
a Hollywood agent?

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:34.000
One thing you see when you look
at this location map

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.000
of the Seven Daughters

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:38.000
is that their tribes had all
migrated thousands of miles

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:40.000
from their original
African home.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:45.000
MAN:
You can see how much of
our environment has changed.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:49.000
In the last 100,000 years,
we move out of Africa,

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.000
we go to very cold climate,
very warm climate,

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:53.000
very wet, very dry climate,

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:56.000
and the north, south--
everywhere.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:00.000
So we change our habitat
and we develop agriculture,

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:02.000
so we change our diet.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:06.000
We now can live in
very dense habitation,

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:09.000
because the food supply
is now very abundant.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:12.000
And once you live
in such close proximity,

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:17.000
all the pathogens--
bacteria, cholera, malaria,

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:19.000
everything-- just multiply.

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:22.000
SEVERSON:
But this new animal also
has created air-conditioning,

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:25.000
central heat,
and modern medicine,

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:26.000
and that may be changing

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:30.000
the mutation-plus-environment
equation in another way.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:33.000
WU:
A mutation can be
good-becoming-bad

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:36.000
or bad-becoming-good,
because environment changes.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:40.000
When you have mutations
going from bad-to-good

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:43.000
that is evolution,
and in that respect,

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:47.000
human probably has been
evolving the most

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.000
compared to other species.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.000
SEVERSON:
Even without such intervention,

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:54.000
bad mutations that aren't
immediately disabling

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:59.000
occur much faster than natural
selection can weed them out.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.000
WU:
The very common diseases

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:04.000
like cardiovascular disease,
the diabetes, asthma,

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:09.000
and most of the common disease,
are actually caused by these--

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:11.000
we call them
small-effect mutations.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:14.000
Each one by itself
doesn't cause much harm,

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:17.000
but the problem is that
we have so many of them,

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:22.000
and that can, in aggregate,
can be a public health concern.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:28.000
Natural selection is
still able to remove

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:31.000
all the mutations
that come in,

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:34.000
but it's not doing it
fast enough,

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
so before a mutation

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:38.000
gets completely purged
from the population,

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:41.000
it probably would have
a sojourn time,

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:43.000
a retention time,

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:46.000
of a couple hundred generation
in a population.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:49.000
So far, we haven't mentioned
one key element

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:53.000
implied in Darwin's theory
of natural selection: luck.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:57.000
WU:
The central concept is that
of course each mutation has

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:00.000
a very, very small chance
of becoming fixed,

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:02.000
but there are so many of them.

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:04.000
So the analogy would be

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:07.000
that if you buy a million
lottery tickets,

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.000
the chance of hitting
the jackpot is pretty good,

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:11.000
and that is the issue
we are addressing;

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:14.000
that is it true
that in a molecular world

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.000
"survival of the fittest"
does not apply;

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:20.000
it's "survival of the luckiest"?

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:23.000
Recently the Smithsonian
Institutution in Washington D.C.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:26.000
added some new genes
to its collection.

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:29.000
They include photographs
of DNA sequences

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:31.000
believed to belong
to O.J. Simpson,

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
taken during what was called

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:36.000
"the trial of the century"
in 1995.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.000
This genetic evidence
was very controversial

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:41.000
and helped get Simpson acquitted
of murder.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:44.000
It also drew
the nation's attention

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:48.000
to what was then a pretty new
forensic method-- DNA profiling.

00:49:49.000 --> 00:49:50.000
But let's back up a bit.

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:53.000
Forensics is the application
of science to legal problems

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.000
and there's nothing new
about that.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:59.000
Let's turn to our
hitchhiker's guide to the genome

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:01.000
for a history lesson.

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:03.000
( computer beeps )

