00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:27.000
Well, thank you
so very, very much.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:30.000
While we've been investigating
crimes for centuries,

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.000
it's been less than 20 years

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:36.000
since genetics revolutionized
the criminal justice system.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:41.000
In 1984 British geneticist Alec
Jeffreys developed DNA profiling

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:42.000
and it's been shaking up

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:46.000
the process
of solving crimes ever since.

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.000
SEVERSON:
Today Kirk Bloodsworth
is a free man,

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:57.000
making his living on his fishing
boat on the Chesapeake Bay.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.000
But only a few years ago,

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:04.000
Kirk was on the State
of Maryland's death row,

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:08.000
waiting to be executed
for a crime he didn't commit.

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:12.000
In the summer of 1984, a young
girl was raped and murdered

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:13.000
in Kirk's neighborhood.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:16.000
Authorities were sure
Kirk had done it.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:17.000
He lived near the crime scene

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:20.000
and he looked like a police
sketch of the suspected killer.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.000
BLOODSWORTH:
Well, I didn't know
what to think.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:24.000
To tell you the truth,

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:27.000
I was in utter shock and
