Kirk spent two years
on death row

00:52:27.000 --> 00:52:29.000
before his sentence
was reduced to life in prison.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:33.000
He kept hoping someone
would believe he was innocent.

00:52:33.000 --> 00:52:36.000
For nine years,
almost no one did,

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:39.000
until DNA profiling came along.

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:40.000
( computer beeps )

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:42.000
COMPUTER:
About DNA profiling:

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:46.000
DNA-- deoxyribonucleic acid--
is the molecule responsible

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:49.000
for every person's
genetic makeup.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:52.000
It is composed
of four nucleotide bases,

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:54.000
arranged in a double helix
or spiral.

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:58.000
DNA is in virtually every cell
in the human body.

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:01.000
With the exception of identical
or monozygotic twins,

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:03.000
no two people have the same DNA.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:06.000
Since each person's DNA sequence
is unique,

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:09.000
DNA evidence collected
from a crime scene

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.000
can link a suspect to a crime
or eliminate one from suspicion

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:15.000
in the same way
that fingerprints are used.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:19.000
This is called a DNA profile.

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
SEVERSON:
In prison, Kirk read a book

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:24.000
about how DNA testing in England
had helped police find a killer.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:29.000
He was sure it could help him,
too, in a different way.

00:53:29.000 --> 00:53:32.000
I felt that if it
could prove somebody did it,

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:35.000
it could also prove
that they didn't do it.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:38.000
SEVERSON:
When Kirk was sentenced
back in 1985,

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:41.000
biological samples
weren't tested for DNA,

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:46.000
but by the early '90s, forensic
scientists could test for it--

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:48.000
even very small amounts.

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:49.000
When a semen stain

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:51.000
on the murdered girl's clothing
was tested,

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:55.000
it came back negative
for Kirk's DNA.

00:53:55.000 --> 00:53:57.000
He was pardoned and became

00:53:57.000 --> 00:54:02.000
the first death row inmate ever
to be freed by DNA evidence.

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:06.000
The re killer
is still out there,

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:08.000
and all of this
won't be complete

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:11.000
until the real one
is behind bars.

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:15.000
With the advent
of the DNA technology, uh,

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:18.000
it's revolutionized
forensic science

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.000
at least to the extent

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:23.000
that fingerprints did
a hundred years ago.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.000
It's... it's easily

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:30.000
one of the single most important
revolutions in forensic science

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:32.000
in the last two decades.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:33.000
SEVERSON:
Paul Ferrara

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:36.000
is director of Virginia's
Division of Forensic Sciences.

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.000
He says DNA technology
has changed

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:41.000
almost every aspect
of law enforcement

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:44.000
from the crime scene
to the courtroom.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:47.000
FERRARA:
They are changing the way
they look at potential evidence.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:50.000
Anything that might contain

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:54.000
some biological, uh, remnant
of an individual

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:57.000
is being collected

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:01.000
and it can be dental floss,
toothbrushes, um,

00:55:01.000 --> 00:55:05.000
hairbrushes, uh, you name it.

00:55:05.000 --> 00:55:08.000
If it's been in contact
with a perpetrator,

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:13.000
it's entirely possible
for us to develop a DNA profile.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:16.000
Ten years ago
they wouldn't even conceive

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:19.000
of collecting something
like that.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:22.000
SEVERSON:
Authorities now have stacks
of evidence to test.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:26.000
They look for hair,
saliva, blood or semen--

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:28.000
anything that might yield DNA.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:32.000
Even microscopic quantities
are sufficient for testing.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:35.000
FERRARA:
In the early days
of DNA technology,

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:39.000
uh, you'd require a blood stain
the size of a quarter

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
to get a DNA profile.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:45.000
With the advent
of the new technologies today,

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:49.000
we're able to develop
a DNA profile

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:53.000
from material that can't
even be seen with the naked eye.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:56:00.000
SEVERSON:
The most common type
of DNA analysis today uses PCR,

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:04.000
which stands
for "polymerase chain reaction."

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:06.000
PCR allows investigators
to analyze evidence

00:56:06.000 --> 00:56:10.000
that couldn't be tested before
because there wasn't enough DNA

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:12.000
or it was of poor quality.

00:56:12.000 --> 00:56:15.000
PCR copies the DNA
over and over again--

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:18.000
a kind of chemical Xeroxing.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:22.000
This amplification process
creates enough DNA

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:23.000
to generate a profile.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:29.000
But with small amounts of DNA,
a sample is easily contaminated.

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:32.000
That's when DNA from
an outside source gets mixed up

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:34.000
with the DNA being tested.

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:37.000
It can happen
when someone sneezes on a sample

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:39.000
or handles it with bare hands.

00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:43.000
Contamination of evidence
was one of the many charges made

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:45.000
by the O.J. Simpson
defense team.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:48.000
But even if a sample
is contaminated,

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:51.000
scientists say the original DNA
is still around.

00:56:51.000 --> 00:56:59.000
FERRARA:
There's nothing in DNA testing
that would allow an examiner

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:04.000
to mistakenly identify
one DNA profile

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:05.000
as belonging to someone else.

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:07.000
If you contaminate a sample,

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:12.000
you have just introduced
a second DNA profile

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:13.000
on top of the original.

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:17.000
It doesn't change
the DNA profile.

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:20.000
SEVERSON:
All lab workers in Virginia

00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:22.000
have their own DNA profiles
on record.

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:27.000
So if their DNA has contaminated
a sample, they can identify it.

00:57:27.000 --> 00:57:31.000
But how do you decide
whose DNA it is?

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:34.000
Well, it turns out that while
we're nearly 100% the same,

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:37.000
there are a few sections
of our genetic code

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:39.000
where we differ quite a bit.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:45.000
13 of those spots are typically
used to generate a DNA profile.

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.000
FERRARA:
In recent years,

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:50.000
all of the forensic science
community in the U.S.

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:54.000
and most of the forensic
community around the world

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:56.000
use these same genetic markers.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:03.000
These portions of DNA are called
STRs, or short tandem repeats.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:08.000
They're portions of the DNA sort
of between the actual genes.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:11.000
SEVERSON:
The real investigative power
of DNA

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:13.000
is in cases
where there is no suspect.

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:17.000
This CODIS database
contains DNA profiles

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:19.000
from convicted criminals.

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:22.000
Authorities link unknown DNA
left at a crime scene

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.000
with the DNA in the database.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:27.000
Sometimes they find
a perfect match--

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:29.000
what's called "a cold hit."

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:31.000
MAN:
We develop a DNA profile

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:32.000
from the evidence in this case

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:36.000
and then search the database
against convicted offenders,

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:40.000
and the computer search finds

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:42.000
that an individual
in the database

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:45.000
actually is completely matching
the profile from the evidence.

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:47.000
And then we are able
to give the police a name

00:58:47.000 --> 00:58:49.000
of an individual to go talk to,

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:52.000
to investigate further,
helping them solve the case

00:58:52.000 --> 00:58:54.000
when they have no idea
where to look

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:55.000
or who committed a crime.

00:58:57.000 --> 00:59:00.000
SEVERSON:
And DNA, like justice, is blind.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:03.000
If you're guilty,
it's your worst enemy.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:06.000
If you're innocent,
it's your best friend.

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:09.000
